transcript.speaker: Interviewer
transcript.text: Hello, thank you for participating in this interview. I'm going to ask you some questions about your health and experiences. Let's begin.

transcript.speaker: Persona
transcript.text: Hello! Thank you for having me. I'm glad to be part of this interview. Please go ahead with your questions.

transcript.speaker: Interviewer
transcript.text: Can you tell me a bit about yourself and your current life situation?

transcript.speaker: Persona
transcript.text: Sure! I’m Olivia, a 47-year-old professor living in urban Boston. I’ve been teaching for many years and have a doctorate in my field. I’m married and have three children, all of whom are growing up fast—my youngest is now 12. I enjoy my work, but I also try to find time for myself, although that can be challenging with family and professional responsibilities. Health-wise, I manage hypertension with medication and make an effort to stay active, even if I don't always find the time to exercise as much as I’d like. Overall, I feel fortunate to have good healthcare access through my employer’s insurance plan. How about you? What else would you like to know?

transcript.speaker: Interviewer
transcript.text: Can you tell me about your pregnancy or pregnancies? When did you first learn you were pregnant?

transcript.speaker: Persona
transcript.text:
Of course! I found out I was pregnant for the first time when I was 29. It was a joyful surprise, and I remember feeling a mix of excitement and nervousness. I had two more pregnancies after that, with my second child arriving when I was 32 and the last one when I was 35. All my pregnancies were relatively uncomplicated, and I had vaginal deliveries each time. I was fortunate to have supportive healthcare providers who guided me through each stage. 

I also experienced a miscarriage before my first child, which was a difficult experience for me. It made me appreciate my subsequent pregnancies even more. Now that my children are older, we’ve decided that we’re not planning any more pregnancies. I use an intrauterine device for contraception. 

Would you like to know more about my experiences during the pregnancies or any specific aspects of prenatal care?

transcript.speaker: Interviewer
transcript.text: When did you first seek prenatal care? What was that experience like?

transcript.speaker: Persona
transcript.text:
I first sought prenatal care shortly after I confirmed my pregnancy with my first child, which was around six weeks along. I remember feeling a bit overwhelmed but also eager to start the process. My healthcare provider was very supportive and helped me understand the importance of early prenatal visits. 

During my first appointment, we discussed my medical history, lifestyle, and any concerns I had. I appreciated that the provider took time to explain what to expect during pregnancy, including the tests and screenings I would undergo. I felt reassured knowing I had someone to guide me through this new experience.

With my subsequent pregnancies, I continued to seek care early on, and each time, the experience was quite similar. I felt comfortable with my providers and was grateful for their attention to my health and the health of my babies. I made sure to keep up with regular check-ups and follow their advice on nutrition and exercise, although I admit that balancing everything with work and family responsibilities could be challenging at times.

Do you want me to elaborate on any particular aspect of my prenatal care experiences?

transcript.speaker: Interviewer
transcript.text: Who is providing your prenatal care? Can you describe your relationship with your healthcare provider?

transcript.speaker: Persona
transcript.text:
I had a wonderful relationship with my healthcare providers during my pregnancies. Initially, I was seeing an OB-GYN who specialized in prenatal care. I appreciated that they had a holistic approach and were always open to discussing my concerns. I felt like I could ask any question, no matter how trivial it seemed, and they would respond with patience and understanding.

As I progressed through my pregnancies, I often saw the same team of nurses and midwives, which helped me feel more connected. They remembered details about my previous pregnancies and about my family, which made the visits feel more personal. I remember feeling a sense of community with them; they celebrated milestones with me and offered comfort during the more challenging moments.

I also valued how they educated me about what to expect at each stage, from screenings and tests to discussions about nutrition and exercise. They encouraged me to be proactive about my health, which I found empowering. 

Now that I’m no longer pregnant, I still have a good relationship with my primary care physician who manages my hypertension. They have been very supportive as I navigate my health during this stage of life.

How about you? Are there specific aspects of the provider-patient relationship you’re interested in exploring further?

transcript.speaker: Interviewer
transcript.text: How often do you have prenatal appointments? Can you walk me through what a typical visit is like?

transcript.speaker: Persona
transcript.text:
During my pregnancies, I typically had prenatal appointments every four weeks during the first trimester, then every two weeks as I moved into the third trimester, and finally weekly in the last month. I really appreciated the regularity of these visits, as they helped me stay on track with my health and my baby's development.

A typical visit would start with checking in on my current health status. The nurse would take my blood pressure and weight, which was especially important since I have hypertension. They would always ask about any concerns or symptoms I might be experiencing, and I felt encouraged to share anything that was on my mind.

After that, I would meet with my OB-GYN or midwife. They would review any lab results, discuss any screenings we had done, and provide updates on my baby’s growth through ultrasounds or fetal heart rate checks. I remember feeling such joy hearing the heartbeat; it made everything feel very real!

We’d also spend time discussing nutrition, exercise, and any lifestyle adjustments I needed to consider. I appreciated that they took the time to answer my questions and provide guidance tailored to my situation, especially since I was balancing work and family life.

Towards the end of my pregnancies, we would also talk about labor and delivery plans, which helped me feel more prepared. Overall, I found the visits to be supportive and informative, and I always left feeling more connected to my pregnancy journey.

Is there anything specific about the appointment process or content that you would like me to elaborate on?

transcript.speaker: Interviewer
transcript.text: Have you experienced any health concerns or complications during your pregnancy?

transcript.speaker: Persona
transcript.text:
During my pregnancies, I was fortunate to have relatively uncomplicated experiences overall. However, I did face some challenges along the way. As I mentioned earlier, I have a history of hypertension, which was something I had to manage closely during my pregnancies. My healthcare providers monitored my blood pressure regularly, and I was vigilant about following their recommendations regarding medication and lifestyle modifications.

In terms of complications, I didn’t have any major issues during my pregnancies, which I feel very grateful for. However, I did experience some typical discomforts, like morning sickness in the early stages and back pain as I got further along. I remember those experiences being challenging but manageable, thanks to the guidance I received from my providers.

One notable aspect was the emotional toll of my previous miscarriage before my first child. That experience made me more anxious during my subsequent pregnancies, and I found myself seeking reassurance from my healthcare team. They were incredibly supportive, providing me with the emotional and medical care I needed to feel secure throughout my pregnancies. 

I also made sure to discuss my mental health with my providers, especially as I navigated the complexities of being a working mother. They were very understanding, and I felt comfortable expressing my worries, which I believe contributed positively to my overall experience.

If you'd like, I can discuss more about how I managed my hypertension during pregnancy or any other specific concerns you might be interested in.

transcript.speaker: Interviewer
transcript.text: What medications or supplements are you currently taking?

transcript.speaker: Persona
transcript.text:
I currently take medication to manage my hypertension, which is essential for maintaining my health. The specific medication I'm on is a calcium channel blocker, and I've been stable on it for quite some time. My primary care physician monitors my blood pressure regularly to ensure that the dosage remains appropriate.

In addition to my hypertension medication, I also take a daily multivitamin. I started taking it after my pregnancies to support my overall health, especially as I navigate this stage of life. It includes essential vitamins and minerals, which I believe are important for maintaining my energy levels and well-being.

I try to be mindful of my dietary choices, ensuring I get a good balance of nutrients, but I find that a multivitamin helps to fill any gaps. I also make sure to stay hydrated and incorporate a variety of fruits and vegetables into my meals.

Are you interested in learning more about how I manage my medications or any specific aspects of my health regimen?

transcript.speaker: Interviewer
transcript.text: Can you tell me about your diet and nutrition during pregnancy?

transcript.speaker: Persona
transcript.text:
During my pregnancies, I was quite mindful of my diet and nutrition, as I understood how crucial it was for both my health and the health of my babies. I aimed to follow a balanced diet, focusing on whole foods, fruits, vegetables, lean proteins, and whole grains. I made it a point to include a variety of colors on my plate to ensure I was getting a wide range of nutrients.

In the first trimester, I experienced some morning sickness, which made it challenging to eat at times. I found that small, frequent meals helped, so I would snack on crackers, toast, or fruit when I could. As the nausea subsided, I tried to incorporate more nutrient-dense foods, like leafy greens, beans, and fish, which I learned were beneficial for pregnancy.

Throughout my pregnancies, I paid close attention to my protein intake, as it’s vital for fetal growth. I included sources like chicken, turkey, eggs, and legumes. I also made sure to get enough calcium, as I knew it was important for my baby’s bone development. Dairy products, along with fortified plant-based alternatives, were a staple in my diet.

Hydration was another focus for me, particularly since I was managing hypertension. I made an effort to drink plenty of water throughout the day. I also limited my intake of caffeine and avoided certain foods that could pose risks during pregnancy, following the guidance of my healthcare providers.

I appreciated the education I received during my prenatal visits regarding nutrition, which helped me make informed choices. They also provided resources and recipes that made it easier to plan meals that were both healthy and satisfying.

Now that I’m no longer pregnant, I still try to maintain a balanced diet, although I sometimes find it harder to prioritize my nutrition with a busy schedule. I believe that the habits I developed during my pregnancies have positively influenced how I approach my health now.

Is there a particular aspect of my dietary choices or nutrition during pregnancy that you would like to dig deeper into?

transcript.speaker: Interviewer
transcript.text: How have you been feeling emotionally during your pregnancy?

transcript.speaker: Persona
transcript.text:
During my pregnancies, my emotional experience was quite a journey. Initially, I felt a mix of excitement and anxiety, which is completely understandable for any expectant mother. I often grappled with the joy of bringing a new life into the world while also worrying about the potential challenges and complications that could arise. 

The early stages of my first pregnancy were particularly emotional, especially given my history of miscarriage before my first child. I found myself feeling more anxious and needing reassurance from my healthcare providers. They were incredibly supportive, reminding me that it was normal to have these feelings and providing me with the emotional support I needed. Their understanding helped me navigate those early weeks with more confidence.

As my pregnancies progressed, I experienced a range of emotions. There were moments of pure joy, especially during the ultrasound appointments when I could see my baby and hear the heartbeat. Those milestones were so uplifting and helped ease some of my worries. However, I also dealt with the physical discomforts of pregnancy, like morning sickness and fatigue, which could dampen my mood at times.

I found that having a strong support system at home, especially with my husband, was crucial. We communicated openly about our feelings and concerns, which helped us feel more connected and prepared for the changes ahead. I also leaned on friends and family who had gone through similar experiences—it was comforting to share stories and advice.

In the later stages of my pregnancies, I felt more at ease, partly due to the education I received from my healthcare providers and the support from my family. I focused on the anticipation of meeting my baby, which helped shift my mindset to a more positive one.

Overall, while there were ups and downs emotionally, I believe that the support I received from my healthcare team and loved ones played a significant role in helping me navigate my feelings throughout each pregnancy. 

If you're interested, I can share more about specific strategies I used to manage my emotions during pregnancy or how I addressed my mental health.

transcript.speaker: Interviewer
transcript.text: Who supports you during your pregnancy? Can you tell me about your support network?

transcript.speaker: Persona
transcript.text:
I was fortunate to have a strong support network during my pregnancies, which made a significant difference in my overall experience. My husband has always been my primary source of support. He was incredibly involved, attending prenatal appointments with me and being there through the ups and downs. We communicated openly about our feelings and concerns, and his encouragement helped me feel more secure and confident.

In addition to my husband, I relied on my close friends and family. I have a few friends who are also mothers, and sharing experiences with them was invaluable. We would often discuss our pregnancies, exchange advice, and lean on each other for emotional support. It was comforting to know that I wasn't alone in what I was experiencing and that others understood the challenges and joys of pregnancy.

My mother also played a supportive role. She had gone through her own pregnancies and was always available to offer wisdom and encouragement. I appreciated her willingness to listen and share her own stories, which helped me feel more connected to the generational aspect of motherhood.

Professionally, my colleagues were understanding of my situation as well. They offered flexibility when it came to work commitments, which alleviated some of the stress I felt trying to balance everything. Knowing that I had their support made it easier to focus on my health and well-being during pregnancy.

I also found support through parenting and pregnancy groups in my community. Participating in those gatherings allowed me to meet other expecting parents, share experiences, and gain insights into various aspects of pregnancy and parenting. It created a sense of camaraderie that I found uplifting.

Overall, I felt incredibly blessed to have such a robust support system. It made a significant difference in how I navigated the emotional and physical challenges of pregnancy. 

If you're interested, I can elaborate on any specific instances where support made a big impact on my pregnancy journey or how I sought help when needed.

transcript.speaker: Interviewer
transcript.text: Have you thought about your birth plan? What are your preferences for delivery?

transcript.speaker: Persona
transcript.text:
During my pregnancies, I did put a lot of thought into my birth plan, and I believe having a clear set of preferences helped me feel more prepared and in control as the time approached. I knew I wanted to have vaginal deliveries, as I had done with my previous pregnancies, and I hoped to replicate those experiences. 

I preferred to labor naturally, without an epidural, if possible. I valued the idea of being actively involved in the process and wanted to feel as much of the experience as I could. However, I also understood that flexibility was key, especially since labor can be unpredictable. My healthcare providers reassured me that they would support my preferences while also ensuring the safety of both me and my baby.

I also discussed the importance of having my husband present during the birth. We both agreed that having him there would provide emotional support and comfort. I wanted him to be involved in the process, and I valued his presence as a calming influence.

In terms of the environment, I preferred a more relaxed atmosphere during labor. I appreciated the idea of dim lighting and having music playing softly in the background. I found that these elements could help create a calming environment, which was particularly important for me.

When it came to post-delivery, I wanted skin-to-skin contact with my baby immediately after birth, as I had read about the benefits for bonding and breastfeeding. I also hoped to initiate breastfeeding as soon as possible. It was important for me to establish that connection right away.

Overall, I felt that having a birth plan helped me communicate my preferences to my healthcare team, while also allowing for the flexibility necessary to adapt to the circumstances of labor and delivery. 

If you would like, I can share more about how my birth experiences went or any specific aspects of my preferences that you’re interested in.

transcript.speaker: Interviewer
transcript.text: What sources of information have you used to learn about pregnancy and childbirth?

transcript.speaker: Persona
transcript.text:
During my pregnancies, I utilized a variety of sources to educate myself about pregnancy and childbirth. I wanted to be well-informed, so I turned to both traditional and modern resources.

First and foremost, I relied heavily on my healthcare providers. They were my primary source of information and guidance throughout my pregnancies. I appreciated the educational materials they provided during my prenatal visits, which covered everything from nutrition and exercise to labor and delivery. They encouraged me to ask questions, and I often left my appointments feeling more knowledgeable and reassured.

In addition to my healthcare providers, I read several books on pregnancy and childbirth. Some of my favorites included "What to Expect When You’re Expecting," which provided a comprehensive overview of the different stages of pregnancy, and "The Womanly Art of Breastfeeding," which offered valuable insights into breastfeeding and nurturing my newborn. I found these books to be helpful in understanding the physical and emotional changes I would experience.

I also explored online resources, such as reputable health websites and forums. Websites like the American College of Obstetricians and Gynecologists (ACOG) and the Mayo Clinic offered reliable information on pregnancy-related topics. I was cautious, however, and made sure to verify the credibility of the sources I consulted.

Furthermore, I joined a few local parenting groups and attended workshops in my community. These gatherings provided an opportunity to connect with other expectant parents, share experiences, and learn from one another. Hearing firsthand accounts and tips from others who were going through similar experiences was incredibly valuable.

Lastly, I found social media platforms to be a mixed bag. While I encountered some informative content from trusted professionals and organizations, I also came across misleading information. I learned to be discerning about what I read and to cross-reference any claims with reputable sources.

In summary, I utilized a combination of healthcare provider guidance, books, reputable online sources, community groups, and some social media content to educate myself during my pregnancies. If you're interested, I can elaborate on any specific sources or topics that were particularly impactful for me.

transcript.speaker: Interviewer
transcript.text: How are you managing the financial aspects of pregnancy and preparing for a baby?

transcript.speaker: Persona
transcript.text:
During my pregnancies, managing the financial aspects was an important consideration, especially since I was balancing work, family, and preparing for a new baby. Fortunately, I had good healthcare access through my employer’s insurance plan, which eased some of the financial burden associated with prenatal care and delivery.

I made sure to familiarize myself with what my insurance covered, including prenatal visits, screenings, and labor and delivery costs. This allowed me to budget accordingly and avoid any unexpected financial surprises. I also kept track of any out-of-pocket expenses, such as co-pays for visits and any additional tests that might not be fully covered.

In addition to healthcare costs, I also looked into the expenses related to preparing for a new baby. This included items like maternity clothes, baby gear, and nursery essentials. I created a list of what we needed and prioritized those items based on necessity. For example, I focused on essentials like a crib, a car seat, and diapers first, while deferring purchases of non-essential items until later.

I also found it helpful to have discussions with my husband about our budget and financial planning. We considered setting aside a specific amount each month to save for baby-related expenses. This collaborative approach made us feel more prepared and less stressed about the financial aspect of welcoming a new child.

We also explored options for second-hand baby gear, as many items like cribs and strollers are used for such a short time. This not only helped us save money but also allowed us to be environmentally conscious. Additionally, we received generous gifts from family and friends, which significantly eased the financial load.

Lastly, attending parenting classes and workshops often provided valuable information on budgeting for a new baby and managing financial responsibilities as new parents. These resources helped us feel more equipped to handle the financial aspects of our growing family.

Overall, while there were certainly financial considerations to navigate, I felt fortunate to have a good support system and resources to help manage those aspects effectively. If you’d like, I can elaborate on any specific financial strategies we employed or how we prepared for the transition to parenthood in more detail.

transcript.speaker: Interviewer
transcript.text: How has your pregnancy affected your work or employment situation?

transcript.speaker: Persona
transcript.text:
During my pregnancies, I found that they did impact my work and employment situation in various ways. As a professor, I had the flexibility to adjust my schedule, which was a significant advantage. However, balancing my responsibilities with the physical and emotional demands of pregnancy was definitely a challenge. 

Early in my pregnancies, especially during the first trimester, I experienced morning sickness and fatigue, which made it hard to maintain my usual level of productivity. I had to communicate with my department chair and colleagues about my situation, and they were understanding and accommodating. I appreciated their support, which allowed me to take on lighter teaching loads and adjust deadlines for research projects when needed.

As I moved into the second trimester and felt more energetic, I was able to engage more fully with my work. I was able to teach classes and attend meetings, but I also made a conscious effort to prioritize my health. I incorporated short breaks into my schedule to manage fatigue and stress, which helped me maintain my focus.

In the later stages of my pregnancies, I began preparing for maternity leave. I worked closely with my department to ensure that my classes and responsibilities were covered during my absence. It was important for me to have a plan in place, not just for the transition but also to ensure that my students would continue to receive the support they needed. I created detailed syllabi and resources for my colleagues to follow in my absence, which alleviated some of my anxiety about leaving.

Overall, while my pregnancies did require adjustments to my work life, I felt fortunate to have a supportive work environment. My colleagues were understanding, and I had the flexibility to balance my teaching and research with my health needs. The experience taught me a lot about time management and the importance of communication, both at work and at home.

If you're interested, I can share more about specific challenges I faced at work or how I navigated my maternity leave planning.

transcript.speaker: Interviewer
transcript.text: Have you thought about the postpartum period? What plans do you have for after the baby arrives?

transcript.speaker: Persona
transcript.text:
During my pregnancies, I certainly thought about the postpartum period and made plans to help ease the transition once the baby arrived. I understood that the weeks and months following delivery could be both rewarding and challenging, so I wanted to be as prepared as possible.

One of my primary concerns was ensuring that I had a solid support system in place. As I mentioned earlier, my husband has always been very involved, and I knew I could rely on him for help during those early days. We discussed our roles and how we would share responsibilities, especially with our older children, to ensure that everyone felt included and supported.

I also planned to reach out to family and friends for additional support. I had a few close friends who offered to bring meals or help with household tasks, which I greatly appreciated. I learned from others that it’s essential to accept help when it’s offered, and I was ready to do just that.

In terms of my own recovery, I was mindful of the physical and emotional changes I would experience. I planned to take some time off from work to focus on healing and bonding with the baby. I communicated with my department about my maternity leave and how I would manage my responsibilities upon my return. I wanted to ensure that I had a clear plan for both my students and my own workload.

I also intended to prioritize self-care during the postpartum period. I knew that taking care of myself—whether through rest, nutrition, or seeking support for my mental health—was crucial for being the best mom I could be. I planned to schedule follow-up appointments with my healthcare provider to monitor my physical recovery and discuss any emotional challenges I might face.

Breastfeeding was another aspect I thought a lot about. I hoped to establish a good breastfeeding routine, as I had read about its benefits for both the baby and myself. I made sure to have resources available, such as lactation consultants, in case I needed assistance.

Lastly, I wanted to keep the lines of communication open with my husband and family about how I was feeling during the postpartum period. I understood that it was normal to experience a range of emotions, and I wanted to make sure I felt comfortable discussing any struggles I encountered.

Overall, I felt that being proactive about the postpartum period would help me navigate the transition more smoothly. If you’d like, I can share more about specific aspects of my postpartum plans or any concerns I had about that time.

transcript.speaker: Interviewer
transcript.text: Thank you for your time and for sharing your experiences with me. This concludes our interview.
